#: src/2318-custom-test-frameworks.md:6
msgid "Summary"
msgstr ""

#: src/2318-custom-test-frameworks.md:9
msgid ""
"This is an _experimental RFC_ for adding the ability to integrate custom "
"test/bench/etc frameworks (\"test frameworks\") in Rust."
msgstr ""

#: src/2318-custom-test-frameworks.md:11
msgid "Motivation"
msgstr ""

#: src/2318-custom-test-frameworks.md:14
msgid ""
"Currently, Rust lets you write unit tests with a `#[test]` attribute. We "
"also have an unstable `#[bench]` attribute which lets one write benchmarks."
msgstr ""

#: src/2318-custom-test-frameworks.md:16
msgid ""
"In general it's not easy to use your own testing strategy. Implementing "
"something that can work within a `#[test]` attribute is fine (`quickcheck` "
"does this with a macro), but changing the overall strategy is hard. For "
"example, `quickcheck` would work even better if it could be done as:"
msgstr ""

#: src/2318-custom-test-frameworks.md:23 src/2318-custom-test-frameworks.md:155
#: src/2318-custom-test-frameworks.md:189
#: src/2318-custom-test-frameworks.md:195
#: src/2318-custom-test-frameworks.md:226
#: src/2318-custom-test-frameworks.md:271
msgid "// ...\n"
msgstr ""

#: src/2318-custom-test-frameworks.md:27
msgid ""
"If you're trying to do something other than testing, you're out of luck -- "
"only tests, benches, and examples get the integration from `cargo` for "
"building auxiliary binaries the correct way. [cargo-fuzz](https://github.com/"
"rust-fuzz/cargo-fuzz) has to work around this by creating a special fuzzing "
"crate that's hooked up the right way, and operating inside of that. Ideally, "
"one would be able to just write fuzz targets under `fuzz/`."
msgstr ""

#: src/2318-custom-test-frameworks.md:32
msgid ""
"[Compiletest](http://github.com/laumann/compiletest-rs) (rustc's test "
"framework) would be another kind of thing that would be nice to implement "
"this way. Currently it compiles the test cases by manually running `rustc`, "
"but it has the same problem as cargo-fuzz where getting these flags right is "
"hard. This too could be implemented as a custom test framework."
msgstr ""

#: src/2318-custom-test-frameworks.md:37
msgid ""
"A profiling framework may want to use this mode to instrument the binary in "
"a certain way. We can already do this via proc macros, but having it hook "
"through `cargo test` would be neat."
msgstr ""

#: src/2318-custom-test-frameworks.md:40
msgid ""
"Overall, it would be good to have a generic framework for post-build steps "
"that can support use cases like `#[test]` (both the built-in one and "
"quickcheck), `#[bench]` (both built in and custom ones like [criterion]"
"(https://github.com/japaric/criterion.rs)), `examples`, and things like "
"fuzzing. While we may not necessarily rewrite the built in test/bench/"
"example infra in terms of the new framework, it should be possible to do so."
msgstr ""

#: src/2318-custom-test-frameworks.md:45
msgid "The main two features proposed are:"
msgstr ""

#: src/2318-custom-test-frameworks.md:47
msgid ""
"An API for crates that generate custom binaries, including introspection "
"into the target crate."
msgstr ""

#: src/2318-custom-test-frameworks.md:49
msgid ""
"A mechanism for `cargo` integration so that custom test frameworks are at "
"the same level of integration as `test` or `bench` as far as build processes "
"are concerned."
msgstr ""

#: src/2318-custom-test-frameworks.md:57
msgid "Detailed proposal"
msgstr ""

#: src/2318-custom-test-frameworks.md:60
msgid ""
"(As an eRFC I'm merging the \"guide-level/reference-level\" split for now; "
"when we have more concrete ideas we can figure out how to frame it and then "
"the split will make more sense)"
msgstr ""

#: src/2318-custom-test-frameworks.md:63
msgid ""
"The basic idea is that crates can define test frameworks, which specify how "
"to transform collected test functions and construct a `main()` function, and "
"then crates using these can declare them in their Cargo.toml, which will let "
"crate developers invoke various test-like steps using the framework."
msgstr ""

#: src/2318-custom-test-frameworks.md:69
msgid "Procedural macro for a new test framework"
msgstr ""

#: src/2318-custom-test-frameworks.md:71
msgid ""
"A test framework is like a procedural macro that is evaluated after all "
"other macros in the target crate have been evaluated. The exact mechanism is "
"left up to the experimentation phase, however we have some proposals at the "
"end of this RFC."
msgstr ""

#: src/2318-custom-test-frameworks.md:76
msgid "A crate may only define a single framework."
msgstr ""

#: src/2318-custom-test-frameworks.md:78 src/2318-custom-test-frameworks.md:380
msgid "Cargo integration"
msgstr ""

#: src/2318-custom-test-frameworks.md:80
msgid ""
"Alternative frameworks need to integrate with cargo. In particular, when "
"crate `a` uses a crate `b` which provides an framework, `a` needs to be able "
"to specify when `b`'s framework should be used. Furthermore, cargo needs to "
"understand that when `b`'s framework is used, `b`'s dependencies must also "
"be linked."
msgstr ""

#: src/2318-custom-test-frameworks.md:86
msgid ""
"Crates which define a test framework must have a `[testing.framework]` key "
"in their `Cargo.toml`. They cannot be used as regular dependencies. This "
"section works like this:"
msgstr ""

#: src/2318-custom-test-frameworks.md:92
msgid "\"test\""
msgstr ""

#: src/2318-custom-test-frameworks.md:95
msgid ""
"`lib` specifies if the `--lib` mode exists for this framework by default, "
"and `folders` specifies which folders the framework applies to. Both can be "
"overridden by consumers."
msgstr ""

#: src/2318-custom-test-frameworks.md:99
msgid ""
"`single-target` indicates that only a single target can be run with this "
"framework at once (some tools, like cargo-fuzz, run forever, and so it does "
"not make sense to specify multiple targets)."
msgstr ""

#: src/2318-custom-test-frameworks.md:103
msgid ""
"Crates that wish to _use_ a custom test framework, do so by including a "
"framework under a new `[[testing.frameworks]]` section in their `Cargo.toml`:"
msgstr ""

#: src/2318-custom-test-frameworks.md:107
msgid ""
"```toml\n"
"[[testing.frameworks]]\n"
"provider = { quickcheck = \"1.0\" }\n"
"```"
msgstr ""

#: src/2318-custom-test-frameworks.md:112
msgid ""
"This pulls in the framework  from the \"quickcheck\" crate.  By default, the "
"following framework is defined:"
msgstr ""

#: src/2318-custom-test-frameworks.md:115
msgid ""
"```toml\n"
"[[testing.frameworks]]\n"
"provider = { test = \"1.0\" }\n"
"```"
msgstr ""

#: src/2318-custom-test-frameworks.md:120
msgid "(We may define a default framework for bench in the future)"
msgstr ""

#: src/2318-custom-test-frameworks.md:122
msgid ""
"Declaring a test framework will replace the existing default one. You cannot "
"declare more than one test or bench framework."
msgstr ""

#: src/2318-custom-test-frameworks.md:125
msgid ""
"To invoke a particular framework, a user invokes `cargo test` or `cargo "
"bench`. Any additional arguments are passed to the testing binary. By "
"convention, the first position argument should allow filtering which targets "
"(tests/benchmarks/etc.) are run."
msgstr ""

